title="Linear algebra as an introduction to abstract mathematics">Linear algebra as an introduction to abstract mathematics</fr:link> Lemma 3.2.2</fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> be a positive integer, let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{0},…,a_{n}\in \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{n}\neq 0]]></fr:tex>. We define the function <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon \mathbb {C}\to \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> by
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[f(z)=a_{n}z^{n}+…+a_{1}z+a_{0}]]></fr:tex>
Then the following all hold:</fr:p><fr:ol><fr:li>For any <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[w\in \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(w)=0]]></fr:tex> if there exists a polynomial <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g\colon \mathbb {C}\to \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> of degree <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\deg (g)=n-1]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(z)=(z-w)g(z)]]></fr:tex>;</fr:li>
<fr:li>There are at most <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> distinct complex numbers <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[w\in \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> for which <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(w)=0]]></fr:tex>; i.e., <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> has at most <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> distinct roots;</fr:li>
<fr:li>(Fundamental theorem of algebra, 2.0) There exists <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n+1]]></fr:tex> complex numbers <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[w_{0},…,w_{n}\in \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> (not necessarily distinct) such that
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[f(z)=w_{0}(z-w_{1})(z-w_{2})(…)(z-w_{n})]]></fr:tex>
In other words, every polynomial function with coefficients over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> can be factored into linear factors over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex></fr:li></fr:ol></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter><fr:tree
