title="Linear algebra as an introduction to abstract mathematics">Linear algebra as an introduction to abstract mathematics</fr:link> Theorem 3.1.2</fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  D\to \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> be a continuous function on the closed disc <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[D_{R}=\{(x_{1},x_{2})\in \mathbb {R}^{2}\mid  x_{1}^{2}+x_{2}^{2}\leq  R^{2}\}]]></fr:tex> of radius <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is bounded and attains its minimum and maximum values on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex>. In other words, there exists points <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x_{\text {min}},x_{\text {max}}\in  D]]></fr:tex> such that for all <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  D]]></fr:tex> we have
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[f(x_{\text {min}})\leq  f(x)\leq  f(x_{\text {max}})]]></fr:tex></fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
