display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in \mathbb {N}_{0}]]></fr:tex> be a non-negative integer. Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{0},…,a_{n}\in \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> be complex numbers. Then we call the expression
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[p(z)=a_{n}z^{n}+…+a_{1}z+a_{0}]]></fr:tex>
a <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Polynomial</html:dfn> in the variable <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[z]]></fr:tex> with <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Coefficients</html:dfn> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{0}]]></fr:tex>, …, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{n}]]></fr:tex>. If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n\neq 0]]></fr:tex>, we call <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> the <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Degree</html:dfn> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> usually writing <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\deg (p)=n]]></fr:tex>. We call <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{n}]]></fr:tex> the <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Leading Coefficient</html:dfn> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p(z)]]></fr:tex>. When <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{n}=1]]></fr:tex> we call <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p(z)]]></fr:tex> <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Monic</html:dfn>.</fr:p><fr:p>If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n=a_{0}=0]]></fr:tex>, then we call <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p(z)=0]]></fr:tex> the <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Zero Polynomial</html:dfn>. Convention dictates <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\deg (0)=-\infty ]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><fr:p>We also call:</fr:p><fr:ul><fr:li>degree zero polnomials are called <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">constant polynomials</html:dfn></fr:li>
<fr:li>degree one polnomials are called <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">linear polynomials</html:dfn></fr:li>
<fr:li>degree two polnomials are called <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">quadratic polynomials</html:dfn></fr:li>
<fr:li>degree three polnomials are called <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">cubic polynomials</html:dfn></fr:li>
<fr:li>degree four polnomials are called <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">quartic polynomials</html:dfn></fr:li>
<fr:li>degree five polnomials are called <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">quintic polynomials</html:dfn></fr:li>
<fr:li>… and so on.</fr:li></fr:ul></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
